# The shell as a machine

Module 01 gave you the loop — **read, run, print, prompt**. Now we open the **run** step.

## Your line is rewritten first

The shell doesn't hand your text straight to a program. It **expands** it — `~`, `$HOME`, `$(...)`, `*.txt` — then the *result* becomes the command + args.

## Then it runs it

```
your line ─▶ expansion (8 phases) ─▶ command + args
                          │
                   fork + exec  (libc → syscall)
                          │
              a running program, streams wired
```

For `ls`, the shell asks the kernel to **`fork`** a child and **`exec`** the program, wiring **stdin / stdout / stderr**. Redirection and pipes just rearrange those streams first.

**This module walks that path** — shortcuts, variables, quoting, streams.
